The Bêkou Trust fund for CAR was launched in July 2014 by the European Union (EU), France, Germany and the Netherlands, to support the country in the post conflict and reconstruction phase using a LRRD approach (Linking Relief, Rehabilitation and Development). Switzerland and Italy later joined the fund.   Under the Bêkou Fund, two Cordaid health projects (112059 and 113430) received funding worth approximately 7.3 m EURO in the period February 2015 to June 2018. This funding for “Support to the restoration of the health system in the Bangassou and Bossangoa Regions "enabled  three Health Districts (Bossangoa (Prefecture Ouham) in  Health Region 3 and Bangassou and Ouango (Prefecture Mbomou) in the Health Region 6) to recover with a final coverage of 53 health facilities serving an estimated population of 341,600 inhabitants. The project approach used Results Based Financing with targeted free healthcare (PLWs and <5) in accordance with the Ministry of Health Guidelines.
Internal and external evaluations and a counter verification  in 2016 and 2018 found good results despite several serious constraints and incidents, namely the looting of the Cordaid office of Bangui in September 2015 and the humanitarian crisis in Bangassou from May 2017, which saw the closure of the regional drug depot of Assomesca,  a local faith-based pharmaceutical NGO,  and in March 2018, the looting of the Cordaid sub-office (AAP) in Bangassou and a major theft of drugs.
 The main findings of the evaluation and counter verification are:
- the health system is operational again;
- the 25 health facilities in the Health District have been reopened, renovated and re-equipped,
- according to quarterly community satisfaction surveys, people are satisfied with the services provided;
- tracer drugs are available;
- free health care is provided to the target group;
- The health district management teams are re-equipped and operational.
Virtually all the quantity and quality indicators have improved

Project goal: To improve the health system and Sexual and Reproductive Health (SRH) service and education in hard-to-reach areas with specific attention for adolescents and women. 

Specific objectives: 

* To strengthen the capacity and supply of the health facilities in the program area to deliver health services; 
* To improve the access of adolescents to SRH information, education and services; 
* To improve access of women to maternal health and family planning services.

Most vulnerable population in targeted areas, according to vulnerability criteria.
The beneficiaries of this project are represented from : 
(i) Widows, girl (heads of household), widowers, persons with disability (reduced mobility), persons with children in poor nutritional situation, unemployed young people (boys and girls) who have left the armed groups among the internal returnees who have lost the livelihood and who had moved to neighboring sub-prefectures or secure and safe localities and villages;  
(ii) The same as above among voluntary repatriates who had taken refuge in neighboring countries, particularly in TChad and Cameroon in the case of the prefecture of Ouham-Pendé and in the DRC in the case of the Mbomou prefecture; and lastly ; 
(iii) Host families/host families who had remained in the area or returned for more than a year and who welcomed the returnees in their family.

L’objectif de ce projet est de contribuer à la réduction des VBG en RCA.
Les objectifs spécifiques sont :
-	Assurer la prévention des VBG à travers la transformation des normes socio culturelles et des comportements pour le respect de l’égalité des sexes à travers la mobilisation des leaders communautaires, des organisations féminines et des SVBG comme acteurs de changement et relais d’information ; 
-	Assurer une prise en charge holistique des SVBG à travers les mécanismes de référencement communautaire, l’accompagnement psychosocial et la réinsertion socio-économique et scolaire des SVBG ;
-	Assurer une meilleure coordination et suivi des activités de VBG dans les zones du projet.

